<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-667-052  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 667 052.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Forbes  August 6 1990 v146 n3 p96(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Silicon reapportionment. (The Republican National Committee isdeveloping software that will reapportion a state's votingdistricts) (Computers/Communications)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pitta, Julie.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Republican National Committee is developing software that willreapportion a state's voting districts on a desktop.andP;  The program,dubbed the 'Fairness Project,' displays demographic informationgraphically, allows three windows to be opened on a screensimultaneously and permits zooming in on geographical areas assmall as a census block.andP;  The program requires a huge data base ofcensus information and an Intel 80386-based microcomputer.andP;  TheParty has already spent $500,000 and invested two years in theprogram development effort.andP;  The 'Fairness Project' will bedistributed to party members and organizations such as theAmerican Civil Liberties Union and the NAACP, in the hope thatthese groups can persuade their Democratic legislators to createminority-dense voting districts.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Product DevelopmentUser-Written SoftwareCustom SoftwareRepublican PartyPolitics.andO;Feature:   illustrationmap.andO;Caption:   California's congressional districts. (map)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>